From 741b8df4bbc5010997887fee38483f3e47f2bec6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ryan Hankins <ryan.hankins@hpe.com>
Date: Mon, 6 Apr 2026 16:52:06 -0500
Subject: [PATCH 4/5] rdma: move flush buffer lifecycle to endpoint scope

In FI_MR_ENDPOINT mode the domain-level flush buffer allocation and MR
registration are skipped (alloc_and_reg_flush_buff sets buffer=MAP_FAILED).
Instead, each endpoint allocates its own GPU flush buffer and registers a
per-endpoint MR in init_rx_buffers().

In non-endpoint-MR mode the domain's already-allocated buffer is aliased
into ep->flush_buff.buffer and the domain-level MR handle is shared via
ep->flush_buff_mr_handle, keeping behaviour identical to before.

All IO-path consumers (recv(), send(), post_flush_req()) are updated to
read from ep->flush_buff.buffer / ep->flush_buff_mr_handle, eliminating
the need to reach through to the domain.  The now-unused 'domain' local
variables in recv() and send() are removed.

fini_rx_buffers() deregisters the per-endpoint MR (endpoint_mr only) and
frees the per-endpoint GPU allocation (buffer_base != nullptr only).

cleanup_resources() is reordered so that fini_rx_buffers() runs before
release_rdma_ep_resources() when endpoint_mr is set, satisfying the
libfabric requirement that MRs bound to an endpoint are closed before
the endpoint itself.  The original order is preserved for non-endpoint-MR
providers.

